Transient‚ however, was the advantage which Paraguay derived from this victory; for peace being ratified between the European powers, the Spaniards restored Nova Colonia to the Portugueze, that they might recover the Havanna, and Manilla‚ capital of the Philip- pineS‚ both which places the English had taken from them. After a few years, war was re- kindled3 and Pedro ZevaHOS, having conquered the Island of Santa Catharina, took it a second time. Finally, in the last peace concluded be- tween the courts of Madrid and Lisbon, it was ceded to the Spanish. This was a bitter loss to the Portugueze, yet by the accession of new territories, many more inlets were opened to them. Cuyaba, a place rich in gold, Matto Grosso, the little fort of S. Rosa, (called La Estacada,> and other colonies, were added to Portugal.
